status: MARC21-007: Specific material designation of sound recording
Special class of sound recording to which the item belongs (e.g., a cylinder).

definition (en): Thin circular objects that vary in diameter (e.g., 7 in., 10 in., 12 in.), on which sound waves, recorded as modulations or pulses, are incised or indented. Compact audio discs are typically 4 3/4 in. in diameter.
Cylindrical objects on which sound waves are incised or indented in a continuous circular groove.
scope note (en): Mass-produced cylinders are made of plastic. Early cylinders were made of tinfoil or wax.

definition (en): Containers holding a single sound tape, run as an endless loop.
A sound recording on film that is not intended to accompany visual images.
scope note (en): Also when it is not known if a sound recording on film is intended to accompany visual images.

definition (en): Roll of paper, for example, for player piano or player organ, on which the notes of a musical composition are represented by perforations in the paper and from which sound can be mechanically produced.
A container holding a narrow, usually 1/8 inch, sound tape on two reels, one to feed (and rewind) and the other to take up the sound tape.
An audiotape-transport system with separate supply (feed) and take-up reels. Usually designated an Open Reel or Reel-to-Reel.
Special material designation for the sound recording is not specified.
A round steel wire on which sound waves are magnetically recorded.
Specific material designation other than sound disc, cylinder, sound cartridge, sound-track film, roll, sound cassette, sound-tape reel, wire recording.
